Name: John Smith
Age: 45
Gender: Male
Occupation: Construction Worker
Ethnicity: Caucasian
Past Medical History: Hypertension, Type 2 Diabetes, History of Alcohol Abuse

Case Report:
John Smith is a 45-year-old male who presented to the emergency department with complaints of severe pain in his left foot. He reported that he had accidentally stepped on a rusty nail while working at a construction site two weeks ago. He initially cleaned the wound and applied topical antibiotics, but the pain and swelling had worsened over the past few days. He also reported fever and chills.

On physical examination, John had significant tenderness and swelling in his left foot, with erythema and warmth extending up to his lower leg. Laboratory tests showed elevated white blood cell count and erythrocyte sedimentation rate. X-rays and MRI of the left foot revealed osteomyelitis involving the first metatarsal bone.

John was admitted to the hospital and started on intravenous antibiotics. He underwent surgical debridement of the infected bone and soft tissues. The wound was left open for daily dressing changes and further debridement as needed. He also received wound care and physical therapy to improve his mobility and prevent complications.

Name: John Smith
Age: 45
Gender: Male
Occupation: Construction worker
Ethnicity: Caucasian
Past Medical History: Hypertension, Type 2 diabetes mellitus

Case Report:

Mr. John Smith presented to the emergency department with severe pain and swelling in his right leg. He reported that the symptoms had been present for the past two weeks and were worsening. Upon examination, his right leg was found to be warm to the touch, and there was erythema and tenderness over the tibia. Mr. Smith had a fever of 101°F and was tachycardic with a heart rate of 110 beats per minute.

Mr. Smith was admitted to the hospital, and further investigations were carried out. Blood tests revealed an elevated white cell count and C-reactive protein level. Imaging studies, including X-rays and a bone scan, were performed, revealing evidence of osteomyelitis in the right tibia.

Mr. Smith was started on intravenous antibiotics, and surgical debridement was performed to remove any necrotic tissue. A vacuum-assisted closure device was applied to facilitate wound healing. The infectious disease team was consulted, and antibiotic therapy was adjusted based on culture and sensitivity results.

The pain became so severe that he was unable to walk and sought medical attention.

On examination, the right foot appeared red, swollen, and warm to touch. There was tenderness over the medial aspect of the foot. The patient had a fever of 101°F.
